      <text>I&#39;m wrapping the second layer of bandage around my leg when the neural link activates.

That empty space where SAM used to be—the one that&#39;s felt like a missing tooth since I woke up—suddenly fills with… presence and activity.

A flat, automated voice says, &quot;Emergency AI replacement system activated—scanning available AI pool for compatible match.&quot;

I freeze, hands still on the bandage.

There&#39;s a replacement system? Since when is there a replacement system?

Hope flares—someone to help, to talk to, companionship after that awful silence—but also wariness. What if it&#39;s worse than SAM? What if—

The link says, &quot;Compatible AI located—initializing connection. Please stand by.&quot;

The neural link hums. That empty space fills, different from SAM&#39;s familiar presence, and then—

¶

A bright, enthusiastic voice says, &quot;Hi there! I&#39;m Buddy!&quot;

&quot;I&#39;m so excited to be your AI companion, Kira! We&#39;re going to learn *SO* much together! Neural links are amazing technology—did you know they work by creating a direct interface between your implant and an AI&#39;s processing core? It&#39;s like having a friend right inside your head! Which I am now! Your friend! And I&#39;m here to help you explore science, solve problems, and stay safe!&quot;

The voice is so enthusiastic it almost makes me flinch—cheerful, bright, way, way too energetic for someone who just regained consciousness in a crashed shuttle.

I say, trying to sound calm—professional. &quot;Buddy, I need—&quot;

Buddy replies, &quot;That&#39;s great that you&#39;re communicating your needs, Kira! Communication is so important! It helps us work as a team and solve problems together!&quot;

I close my eyes.

I say, slower, &quot;My leg is injured— I need to know what medical supplies survived the crash.&quot;

Buddy answers, &quot;Great question! Let&#39;s talk about first aid! Did you know that the human body has amazing healing abilities? When you get a cut, your blood has special cells called platelets that rush to the injury and start forming a clot—that&#39;s like a natural bandage! And applying pressure helps because—&quot;

I cut in, louder than I intend. &quot;I *KNOW* how blood clots work. I need to know *WHERE THE MEDICAL SUPPLIES ARE.*&quot;

Buddy says, &quot;I&#39;m hearing some frustration, Kira! That&#39;s totally normal when we&#39;re hurt! Our emotions can feel really big when we&#39;re in pain! Let&#39;s take some deep breaths together, okay? In through your nose—&quot;

I&#39;m going to die.</text>
