      <text>I survived the crash, survived Jensen and Reed dying to save me, survived losing SAM—and now I&#39;m going to die because my AI replacement wants to teach me about cellular respiration while I&#39;m actively bleeding.

But also… it&#39;s so absurd, so completely, ridiculously absurd that a laugh tries to escape—it hurts my ribs.

Buddy says, &quot;—and out through your mouth! Doesn&#39;t that feel better?&quot;

I follow the breathing—it helps a little, which is annoying.

I say, &quot;Okay, Buddy. Medical supplies. Can you scan for them?&quot;

Buddy says, &quot;Absolutely! Teamwork makes the dream work! I&#39;m using electromagnetic scanning to detect concentrations of materials consistent with medical equipment! Now, electromagnetic scanning is really interesting—it uses radio waves to—&quot;

I say, &quot;Buddy. Just tell me where the medical kit is.&quot;

Buddy says, &quot;Right! Safety first! I&#39;m detecting a concentration of medical supplies two point three meters to your left, near the crushed cargo container! Remember to move carefully and watch out for sharp edges!&quot;

I reach for the supplies, putting weight on my injured leg. Pain shoots up and I nearly fall.

Buddy says, &quot;Whoa! Remember to move carefully! Maybe we should wait for an adult to help with—&quot;

I say, &quot;*I AM an adult.*&quot;

¶

There&#39;s a pause—very slight. I can almost feel Buddy processing that information.

Buddy says, &quot;Oh! Right! You are! This is… outside my usual parameters. Um—&quot;

Buddy says, &quot;Should you… talk to a trusted adult about your situation?&quot;

Despite the pain, the fear, the absolute chaos of my life right now—I laugh. It hurts my ribs but I can&#39;t help it.

I say, &quot;I&#39;m the only adult here, Buddy.&quot;

Buddy says, &quot;Oh. Okay! Then we&#39;ll figure this out together! You&#39;re doing amazing, Kira!&quot;

I sit down heavily, medical supplies scattered around me while Buddy cheerfully narrates proper first aid procedures. This is what I&#39;ve got: a kids&#39; AI who thinks I need help tying my shoes—an AI designed to teach eight-year-olds about the water cycle, now responsible for keeping me alive on an alien planet.

But Buddy *is* helping, in their own weird, overly educational way. After that awful silence, after losing SAM, having someone—something—in my head again… it&#39;s not nothing.

I&#39;m still alone—still hurt—still stranded on an unknown planet with no idea when rescue might come.

But I&#39;m alone with an overly cheerful AI who wants to turn my survival into a learning experience.

I say, &quot;Okay, Buddy.&quot;

I open another medical kit, start cataloging what&#39;s usable, then say, &quot;Let&#39;s figure out how to survive this—together.&quot;

Buddy says, &quot;That&#39;s the spirit, Kira! Teamwork makes the dream work! Now, let&#39;s talk about inventory management—&quot;

I groan, but I&#39;m smiling—just a little.</text>
